<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="342" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="3.[168,776,1302,2093]" pageId="3" pageNumber="342">
Regarding conservation, the phytogeographic domain of the Caatinga has been neglected, with only 1% of its territory belonging to conservation units (
<bibRefCitation author="Leal IR &amp; Silva JMC &amp; Tabarelli M &amp; Lacher Jr. TE" journalOrPublisher="Conservation Biology" pageId="3" pageNumber="342" pagination="701 - 706" part="19" refId="ref2711" refString="Leal IR, Silva JMC, Tabarelli M, Lacher Jr. TE (2005) Changing the course of biodiversity conservation in the Caatinga of northeast- ern Brazil. Conservation Biology 19 (3): 701 - 706. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1523 - 1739.2005.00703. x" title="Changing the course of biodiversity conservation in the Caatinga of northeast- ern Brazil" type="journal article" year="2005">Leal et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
) and little research is carried out, due to the belief that it presents low biological diversity (
<bibRefCitation author="Moro MF &amp; Lughadha EN &amp; Araujo FS &amp; Martins FR" box="[588,764,1669,1693]" journalOrPublisher="The Botanical Review" pageId="3" pageNumber="342" pagination="91 - 148" part="82" refId="ref2768" refString="Moro MF, Lughadha EN, Araujo FS, Martins FR (2016) A Phytogeo- graphical Metaanalysis of the Semiarid Caatinga Domain in Bra- zil. The Botanical Review 82 (2) 91 - 148. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12229 - 016 - 9164 - z" title="A Phytogeo- graphical Metaanalysis of the Semiarid Caatinga Domain in Bra- zil" type="journal article" year="2016">Moro et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). However, contrary to expectations, the Caatinga presents high species richness with a high degree of endemism, including vegetation that is widely diversified with more than 4,600 species of angiosperms, 20% of which are endemic (
<bibRefCitation author="BFG &amp; The Brazil Flora Group" box="[273,387,1835,1860]" journalOrPublisher="Rodriguesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="342" pagination="1085 - 1113" part="66" refId="ref2370" refString="BFG (The Brazil Flora Group) (2015) Growing knowledge: an overview of Seed Plant diversity in Brazil. Rodriguesia 66 (4): 1085 - 1113. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 2175 - 7860201566411" title="Growing knowledge: an overview of Seed Plant diversity in Brazil" type="journal article" year="2015">
<collectionCode box="[273,326,1836,1860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="342">BFG</collectionCode>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Nevertheless, research on the flora of the Caatinga is still insufficient when considering the high richness associated with its environments (
<bibRefCitation author="Souza BIF &amp; Artigas RC &amp; Lima ERV" journalOrPublisher="Mercator" pageId="3" pageNumber="342" pagination="131 - 150" part="14" refId="ref2932" refString="Souza BIF, Artigas RC, Lima ERV (2015) Caatinga e desertificacao. Mercator 14 (1): 131 - 150. http: // doi. org / 10.4215 / RM 2015.1401.0009" title="Caatinga e desertificacao" type="journal article" year="2015">Souza et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="342" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[168,776,1302,2093]" lastBlockId="3.[813,1420,1302,1460]" pageId="3" pageNumber="342">
In this context, the new record of 
<taxonomicName box="[584,775,1969,1993]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Wissadula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="3" pageNumber="342" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hernandioides">
<emphasis box="[584,775,1969,1993]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="342">W. hernandioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the Caatinga domain and 
<collectingRegion box="[489,624,2002,2026]" country="Brazil" name="Pernambuco" pageId="3" pageNumber="342">Pernambuco</collectingRegion>
State emphasizes the importance of expanding botanical collection efforts, especially in areas, as the Brazilian semi-arid, that are still unexplored from a floristic and taxonomic viewpoint. Furthermore, such increased collection efforts would help reinforce the importance of creating new conservation units in the Caatinga, as well as conserve and recover the biodiversity of this domain.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
